  "name": "Relationship Cards — A Couples Oracle",
  "description": "A 54-card oracle deck for couples based on relationship science. Draw three cards together — The Pattern (what's showing up), The Need (what's underneath), The Move (what you could try) — and use them as a mirror for your relationship. Grounded in Gottman's research on the masters and disasters of love, Sue Johnson's Emotionally Focused Therapy, Bowlby's attachment theory, and Linehan's dialectical thinking. No card is bad. Even contempt is pointing toward what the relationship is starving for.\n\n5 suits: Patterns (the big dynamics), Needs (what's underneath), Repairs (moves you can make), Strengths (what's already alive), and Shadows (the hard truths). Designed to be played weekly as a couple's ritual — draw, discuss, journal, repeat.\n\nPUBLIC DOMAIN ILLUSTRATION REFERENCES: Gustav Klimt's 'The Kiss' (1907-1908) and other Secessionist works depicting intimacy and embrace. Edvard Munch's relationship paintings — 'The Dance of Life' (1899-1900), 'Separation' (1896), 'Attraction' (1896). Auguste Rodin sculptures — 'The Kiss' (1882), 'The Cathedral' (hands). Egon Schiele's embrace paintings (1910s). Japanese ukiyo-e depicting couples — Utamaro's bijin-ga. Indian Mughal miniatures of Radha-Krishna embraces. William Blake's illustrations of marriage from 'Songs of Innocence and Experience' (1789-1794).",
  "grammar_type": "tarot",
  "creator_name": "PlayfulProcess",
  "creator_link": "https://lifeisprocess.substack.com/",
